rs of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Spa drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Sebring drivers]]\n[[Category:Mille Miglia drivers]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:English aviators]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force squadron leaders]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clifton College]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chertsey]]\n[[Category:Brighton Speed Trials people]]\n[[Category:British World War II pilots]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name = George Abecassis\n| image =\n| caption =\n| nationality = {{flagicon|GBR}} British\n| birth_name = George Edgar Abecassis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1913|3|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Oatlands, Surrey|Oatlands]], Surrey, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1991|12|18|1913|3|21}}\n| death_place = [[Ibstone]], Buckinghamshire, England\n| record template1 =\n  {{Infobox F1 driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years = {{F1|1951}} \u2013 {{F1|1952}}\n  | Team(s) = [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]]\n  | Races = 2\n  | Championships = 0\n  | Wins = 0\n  | Podiums = 0\n  | Points = 0\n  | Poles = 0\n  | Fastest laps = 0\n  | First race = [[1951 Swiss Grand Prix]]\n  | First win = \n  | Last win = \n  | Last race = [[1952 Swiss Grand Prix]]\n  }}\n| record template2 =\n  {{Infobox Le Mans driver|subbox=yes \n  | Years       = {{24hLM|1950}}\u2013{{24hLM|1951}}, {{24hLM|1953}}\n  | Teams       = [[Aston Martin]]\n  | Best Finish = 5th <small>({{24hLM|1950}}; {{24hLM|1951}})</small>\n  | Class Wins  = 1 <small>({{24hLM|1950}})</small>\n  }}\n| record template3 =\n  {{Infobox military person \n  | embed       = yes\n  | embed_title = Military career \n  | allegiance = {{flagu|United Kingdom }}\n  | branch = {{air force|United Kingdom}}<br/>{{smaller|([[Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve|Volunteer Reserve]])}}\n  | serviceyears = {{circa|1940}}\u20131953<ref name=discharge>{{London Gazette |issue=39878 |date=2 June 1953 |page=3110 |supp=y}}</ref> \n  | rank = [[Squadron leader#RAF usage|Squadron leader]]<ref name=rank>{{London Gazette |issue=36299 |date=21 December 1943 |page=5590 |supp=y}}</ref>\n  | awards = {{bulleted list|[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]<ref name=DFC>{{London Gazette |issue=36997 |date=23 March 1945 |page=1597 |supp=y}}</ref>|[[Mentioned in dispatches]]<ref name=MID>{{London Gazette |issue=36329 |date=11 January 1944 |page=292}}</ref>}}\n  | unit = [[No. 161 Squadron RAF]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=36997 |date=20 March 1945 |page=1597 |supp=y}}</ref>\n  | servicenumber = 115865\n  | battles = [[World War II]]\n  | website = {{URL|tracesofwar.com/persons/39028/Abecassis-George-Edgar.htm|Profile at Traces of War}}\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''George Edgar Abecassis''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DFC}}<ref name=DFC/> (21 March 1913 \u2013 18 December 1991) was a British racing driver, and co-founder of the [[Hersham and Walton Motors|HWM]] [[Formula One]] team.\n\n==Pre-1946 career==\nBorn in [[Oatlands, Surrey|Oatlands]], [[Surrey]], Abecassis was educated at [[Clifton College]].<ref>\"Clifton College Register\" Muirhead, J.A.O. p434: Bristol; J.W Arrowsmith for Old Cliftonian Society; April, 1948</ref> He began circuit racing in 1935 in a modified Austin Seven which became known as ''The Einsitzer''. After taking 1937 as a year away from the track, he acquired an [[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta]] and made a name for himself in English national racing during the 1938 and 1939 seasons. In 1939, he won the [[Imperial Trophy]] [[Formula Libre]] race at [[Crystal Palace (circuit)|Crystal Palace]], driving his Alta, defeating [[Birabongse Bhanudej|Prince Bira]], in the E.R.A. known as ''Romulus'', in a wet race,<ref>''Motor Sport'', November 1938, Page 388.</ref> \"that being the only time it was beaten by a {{cvt|1500|cc|abbr=on}} car in the British Isles.\"<ref>''Motor Sport'', November 1940, Page 202.</ref>\n\nAt one point, Abecassis held the Campbell circuit lap record at [[Brooklands]] at {{convert|72.61|mph|km/h}}<ref>''Motor Sport'', May 1939, Page 135.</ref> On 3 July 1938 Abecassis broke the [[Prescott Speed Hill Climb|Prescott Hill Climb]] record with a climb of 47.85 seconds in his supercharged 1\u00bd-litre Alta.<ref>''Motor Sport'', July 1938, Page 246.</ref>\n\nWhen [[World War II]] broke out he joined the [[Royal Air Force]], as a member of the [[Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve|Volunteer Reserves]], and became an experienced pilot, ultimately becoming a member of the secret \"Moon Squadrons\",<ref name=gp>{{cite web|title= Drivers: George Abecassis |url= http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/drv-abageo.html |work= GrandPrix.com |accessdate=26 November 2007}}</ref> ferrying secret agents in and out of occupied countries in Europe with specially-modified Halifax and Stirling aircraft. During the course of his wartime service Abecassis was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]<ref name=DFC/><ref name=watn>{{cite web|title= The World Championship drivers \u2014 Where are they now? |url= http://www.oldracingcars.com/driver/George_Abecassis |work= OldRacingCars.com |access-date=26 November 2007}}</ref> and was [[mentioned in dispatches]]<ref name=MID/> with the following citation:<ref>{{cite web |author=Halliday, Hugh |url=http://www.rafcommands.com/awards/mention-in-despatches/ |title=Mention-in-Despatches |work=Royal Air Force Commands |publisher= |date=16 February 2014 |access-date=14 September 2019 }}</ref>\n{{block quote|[Abecassis]... has been employed as a Flying Instructor and latterly as Deputy Flight Commander. His keenness and enthusiasm, combined with conscientious and consistent instruction, have always been an inspiration to trainee pilots and his pupils have in every case displayed the hallmark of his careful attention. He has carried out a long spell on the arduous and exacting duties of a Flying Instructor at an Operational Training Unit.|as per ''[[London Gazette]]'', 11 January 1944.}}\n\nAbecassis achieved the rank of [[Squadron leader#RAF usage|squadron leader]],<ref name=rank/> and, following the war, continued as a member of the RAF Volunteer Reserves prior to his discharge in 1953.<ref name=discharge/>\n\n==Post-1946 career==\n{{see also|Hersham and Walton Motors}}\nAfter World War II Abecassis went back to racing, initially with pre-war machinery. He won a race at [[Gransden Lodge Airfield|Gransden Lodge]] in a road-going 3.3-litre [[Bugatti]] on 15 June 1946.<ref>''Motor Sport'', July 1946, Page 143.</ref> In 1947, Abecassis finished second in the Swedish Grand Prix, held on a frozen lake at Vallentuna, driving an E.R.A.<ref>''Motor Sport'', April 1947, Page 98.</ref>  In 1948, he finished second to [[Bob Gerard]] in the Jersey International Road Race.<ref>''Motor Sport'', June 1948, cover.</ref> He became a partner, with [[John Heath (racing driver)|John Heath]], in [[Hersham and Walton Motors]] Ltd., a motor dealership and garage in [[Walton-on-Thames]]. Building on his pre-war association with the Alta marque, Abecassis and HWM assisted in the development of the [[Alta GP]] car,<ref name=watn/> designed to comply with the recently introduced [[Formula One]] regulations.\n\nAfter the failure of this enterprise, Abecassis and Heath decided to construct their own cars under the HWM banner, but retaining Alta engines. Initially the HWM cars were designed to compete in the [[Formula Two]] class, but when the World Championship switched to Formula Two regulations in {{F1|1952}} HWM cars became eligible to compete in the Grand Prix events. During their prime, HWM employed such future stars as [[Stirling Moss]] and [[Peter Collins (racing driver)|Peter Collins]], and the Belgian [[Johnny Claes]] scored their first victory, in the [[Grand Prix des Fronti\u00e8res]] at a [[Chimay Street Circuit|street circuit]] in [[Chimay]], Belgium.<ref name=gp/> Abecassis's HWM team also took a notable victory in the [[BRDC International Trophy|International Trophy]] race at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] in 1952, this time with [[Lance Macklin]] at the wheel. With the reintroduction of Formula One cars to the World Championship in {{F1|1954}}, Abecassis and Heath attempted to produce a competitive car using the 2.5-litre version of the Alta engine but it was not a success;<ref name=gp/> HWM cars only contested two further Grand Prix events after 1953.\n\nIt was with his own HWM cars that Abecassis raced in his only two Formula One World Championship Grands Prix, at the [[Circuit Bremgarten|Bremgarten]] circuit, in the [[1951 Swiss Grand Prix|1951]] and [[1952 Swiss Grand Prix]]. He was more successful as a sports car driver with [[Aston Martin]] and won his class at the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] in {{24hLM|1950}}, sharing his [[Aston Martin DB2|DB2]] with Macklin. He also finished second in the [[12 Hours of Sebring]] in 1953, partnered by [[Reg Parnell]]. In 1953, Abecassis constructed an HWM sports car for his own personal use, powered by a [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]] [[Straight-six engine|straight-6]] engine, with which he successfully contested many national British races until 1956.<ref name=autocourse>{{cite web|title=Driver: Abecassis, George |url=http://www.autocoursegpa.com/driver~driver_id~11549.htm |work=Autocourse Grand Prix Archive |accessdate=27 November 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221183618/http://www.autocoursegpa.com/driver~driver_id~11549.htm |archivedate=21 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Heath was killed in an accident in the [[Mille Miglia]] and Abecassis retired from racing, turning his attention to running the HWM operations. He was the [[Facel Vega]] importer for Britain, while his motor industry connections were aided by the fact that he was married to Angela, the daughter of Aston Martin chairman [[David Brown (entrepreneur)|Sir David Brown]]. He died aged 78, in [[Ibstone]], near [[High Wycombe]], [[Buckinghamshire]].\n\nIn September 2010 his son David Abecassis published a comprehensive biography of his father under the title ''A Passion for Speed''.\n\nHis grandson, Jonathan Abecassis, has an active interest in vintage sports car racing. He competes in the Fifties Sports Car Racing Club (\"FISCAR\") series, driving an [[Austin-Healey 100|Austin Healey 100/4]].\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career highlights===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Position\n! Team\n! Car\n|-\n| 1935\n| [[Aston Clinton Hillclimb|Aston Clinton Speed Trails]]  <ref name=\"georgeabecassis.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.georgeabecassis.com/racelist.html|title=George Abecassis Race List|website=www.georgeabecassis.com|accessdate=8 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602163305/http://www.georgeabecassis.com/racelist.html|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Austin 7|Austin 7 \"Einsitzer\"]]\n|-\n| 1938\n| Easter Road Race  <ref name=\"georgeabecassis.com\"/>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta 2.0 s/c]]\n|-\n| \n| [[Lewes Speed Trials]]  <ref name=\"georgeabecassis.com\"/>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta S]]\n|-\n| \n| British Trophy  <ref name=\"georgeabecassis.com\"/>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta S]]\n|-\n| \n| Crystal Palace Cup  <ref name=\"georgeabecassis.com\"/>\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| \n| [[Alta Car and Engineering Company|Alta S]]\n|-\n| \n| Crystal Palace Grand Prix<ref name=\"racingsportscars.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/driver/results/George-Abecassis-GB.html|title=George Abecassis (GB) - All Results - Racing Sports Cars|website=www.racingsportscars.com|acc