{"title_page": "Mouhamed Niang", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Senegalese association football player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mouhamed Niang\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1999|10|8}}\n| birth_place =\n| currentclub = [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] (On loan from [[Partick Thistle]])\n| clubnumber = 12\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]],[[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Pollok United Soccer Academy]]\n| years1 = 2017-18\n|clubs1 = [[Pollok F.C.|Pollok]]\n|caps1 = ?\n|goals1 = ?\n| years2 = 2019-\n| clubs2 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2019-\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 14\n| goals3 = 1\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1  =\n| nationalcaps1  =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update = 10:57, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Mouhamed Niang''', more commonly known as \u2018Sena\u2019 is a Senegalese football player who currently plays on loan at [[Scottish League One]] side [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], on loan from [[Scottish Championship]] club [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-team/mouhamed-niang-2/</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nMouhamed Niang started his career at [[SJFA West Region Premiership]] side [[Pollok F.C.|Pollok]], after graduating from the Pollok United Soccer Academy in the summer of 2017 after having captained the U19's side the previous season. As the first academy graduate to make the step up, he made his first team debut against Arthurlie in a 1-0 Sectional League Cup win and made his first league start a few games later away to Kirkintilloch Rob Roy in the league. He finished the 2017\u201318 season with 20 appearances. He made 9 appearances in the 2018\u201319 season, scoring his first goal for the Lok in a 4\u20131 win against Maryhill.<ref>https://pollokfc.com/tag/pollok-united-soccer-academy/</ref>\n\n===Partick Thistle===\nNiang signed for [[Scottish Championship]] club [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in September 2018, following a long and complicated work permit application process.<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mohamed-niang-signs-for-reserve-squad/</ref> Niang made his debut for Thistle playing 86 minutes in a 2\u20130 win away to [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]].<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-fixture/montrose-v-partick-thistle-7th-september-2019/</ref> Niang joined [[Scottish League One]] side [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], on loan until January 2020, this loan was later extended until the end of the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mouhamed-niang-joins-montrose-on-loan/</ref><ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/niang-loan-extended-until-the-end-of-season/</ref> Niang signed a one-year contract extension with Thistle in December 2019.<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mouhamed-niang-signs-contract-extension/</ref>\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Senegalese association football player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mouhamed Niang\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1999|10|8}}\n| birth_place =\n| currentclub = [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] (On loan from [[Partick Thistle]])\n| clubnumber = 12\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]],[[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Pollok United Soccer Academy]]\n| years1 = 2017-18\n|clubs1 = [[Pollok F.C.|Pollok]]\n|caps1 = ?\n|goals1 = ?\n| years2 = 2019-\n| clubs2 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2019-\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 14\n| goals3 = 1\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1  =\n| nationalcaps1  =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| club-update = 10:57, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n}}\nMouhamed Niang, more commonly known as \u2018Sena\u2019 is a Senegalese football player who currently plays on loan at [[Scottish League One]] side [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], on loan from [[Scottish Championship]] club [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref> https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-team/mouhamed-niang-2/</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early Career===\nMouhamed Niang started his career at [[SJFA West Region Premiership]] side [[Pollok F.C.|Pollok]], after graduating from the Pollok United Soccer Academy in the summer of 2017 after having captained the U19\u2019s side the previous season. As the first academy graduate to make the step up, he made his first team debut against Arthurlie in a 1-0 Sectional League Cup win and made his first league start a few games later away to Kirkintilloch Rob Roy in the league. He finished the 2017-18 season with 20 appearances. He made 9 appearances in the 2018-19 season, scoring his first goal for the Lok in a 4-1 win against Maryhill.<ref> https://pollokfc.com/tag/pollok-united-soccer-academy/</ref>\n\n===Partick Thistle===\nNiang signed for [[Scottish Championship]] club [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in September 2018, following a long and complicated work permit application process.<ref> https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mohamed-niang-signs-for-reserve-squad/</ref> Niang made his debut for Thistle playing 86 minutes in a 2-0 win away to [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]].<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-fixture/montrose-v-partick-thistle-7th-september-2019/</ref> Niang joined [[Scottish League One]] side [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], on loan until January 2020, this loan was later extended until the end of the 2019-20 season.<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mouhamed-niang-joins-montrose-on-loan/</ref><ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/niang-loan-extended-until-the-end-of-season/</ref> Niang signed a one year contract extension with Thistle in December 2019.<ref>https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/mouhamed-niang-signs-contract-extension/</ref>\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2017-18 \u2192 2017\u201318 (5), one year \u2192 one-year, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mouhamed_Niang"}
{"title_page": "Joanna Mazur", "text_new": "{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Joanna Mazur\n| nickname = Asia\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n|disability = [[Visual impairment]]\n|disability_class = [[T11 (classification)|T11]]\n| event = [[100 metres]]<br>[[200 metres]]<br>[[400 metres]]<br>[[800 metres]]<br>[[1500 metres]]\n| club = START Tarnow\n| coach = Micha\u0142 Stawicki (guide runner)<br>Zbigniew Lewkowicz\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|03|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Szczecin]], [[Poland]]\n| residence = [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland\n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 1.67m\n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{POL}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{POL}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Athletics Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 1500m T11}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 800m T11}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 400m T11}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|Women's 200m T11}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2018 World Para Athletics European Championships|2018 Berlin]]|Women's 400m T11}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2018 World Para Athletics European Championships|2018 Berlin]]|Women's 1500m T11}}\n}}\n\n'''Joanna Mazur''' (born 14 March 1990) is a blind [[Polish people|Polish]] [[Paralympic athletics|Paralympic athlete]] who competes in [[sprint (running)|sprinting]] events in international level events. She has been blind since she was seven years old due to a rare genetic defect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=1420070&wintergames=-1&refreshauto=1|title=Joanna Mazur - IPC Athlete Bio|last=|first=|date=4 April 2020|website=ipc.infostradasports.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefirstnews.com/article/record-breakers-para-athletes-power-to-glory-with-incredible-61-medals-in-european-championships-1922|title=Record Breakers! Para athletes power to glory with incredible 61 medals in European Championships|last=|first=|date=27 August 2018|website=The First News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nMazur was a contestant on [[Dancing with the Stars: Taniec z gwiazdami]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsbeezer.com/polandeng/who-is-blind-joanna-mazur/|title=Who is blind, Joanna Mazur?|last=|first=|date=5 January 2019|website=newsbeezer.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Polish female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Joanna Mazur\n| nickname = Asia\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n|disability = [[Visual impairment]]\n|disability_class = [[T11 (classification)|T11]]\n| event = [[100 metres]]<br>[[200 metres]]<br>[[400 metres]]<br>[[800 metres]]<br>[[1500 metres]]\n| club = START Tarnow\n| coach = Micha\u0142 Stawicki (guide runner)<br>Zbigniew Lewkowicz\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|03|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Szczecin]], [[Poland]]\n| residence = [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland\n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 1.67m\n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{POL}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{POL}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Athletics Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 1500m T11}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 800m T11}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|Women's 400m T11}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|Women's 200m T11}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2018 World Para Athletics European Championships|2018 Berlin]]|Women's 400m T11}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2018 World Para Athletics European Championships|2018 Berlin]]|Women's 1500m T11}}\n}}\n\n'''Joanna Mazur''' (born 14 March 1990) is a blind [[Polish people|Polish]] [[Paralympic athletics|Paralympic athlete]] who competes in [[sprint (running)|sprinting]] events in international level events. \n\nMazur was a contestant on [[Dancing with the Stars: Taniec z gwiazdami]] in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Polish female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "SarahTHunter", "label": "safe", "comment": "References added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joanna_Mazur"}
{"title_page": "AHFS Drug Information Book", "text_new": "<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1968-01|title=Book Review: Russian Drug Index|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/106002806800200109|journal=Drug Intelligence|volume=2|issue=1|pages=21\u201321|doi=10.1177/106002806800200109|issn=1044-6192}}</ref>https://www.ahfsdruginformation.com/2018/{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}{{Third-party|date=January 2018}}{{tone|date=January 2018}}{{context|date=January 2018}}\n{{Underlinked|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n\nOriginally published in 1959 as the [[American Hospital Formulary Service]] (AHFS) by the [[American Society of Health-System Pharmacists]], the '''AHFS DI''' is one of several [[Compendium (software)|compendiums]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=3b064b5a-3d91-4f4e-8161-1330fb6884fa|title=And then there were five: CMS approves Wolters Kluwer Lexi-Drugs\u00ae as the fifth recognized authoritative compendium {{!}} Lexology|last=ElizabethHalpern|first=Hogan Lovells-|last2=Langbein|first2=Stuart M.|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30|last3=Manning|first3=Meredith|last4=Roberts|first4=Beth L.|last5=Lakhani|first5=Ali}}</ref> approved by the [[Social Security Act]] ([https://www.ssa.gov/OP_Home/ssact/title18/1861.htm Section 1861(t)(2)(B)(ii)(I)]) as a source of off-label anti-[[cancer]] [[drug]] use.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Coverage Document|url=https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/details/medicare-coverage-document-details.aspx?MCDId=31&mcdtypename=Compendia&MCDIndexType=6&bc=AgAEAAAAAAAA&|website=Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services|publisher=cms.gov|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalacademies.org/hmd/~/media/af05179e323c4b0c852d2eee55370043.ashx|title=Role of Compendia in Determining what Drugs are Reimbursed|last=Abernethy|first=Amy|date=October 2012|website=National Science Foundation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  It is also the only one left of the originally authorized compendiums.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Butcher|first=Lola|date=2008-06-25|title=Compendia Decisions Impact Off-Label Coverage|journal=Oncology Times|language=en-US|volume=30|issue=12|pages=29\u201330|doi=10.1097/01.COT.0000326167.89228.b6|issn=0276-2234}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20180331040051/http://formularyjournal.modernmedicine.com/formulary-journal/news/clinical/clinical-pharmacology/gain-solid-understanding-compendia-and-its-imp Gain a solid understanding of compendia and its impact on patient access]\". Formulary Journal. 2012-07-01. Retrieved 2018-03-30.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ahfsdruginformation.com/ Official site]\n\n[[Category:Medical books]]\n", "text_old": "https://www.ahfsdruginformation.com/2018/{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}{{Third-party|date=January 2018}}{{tone|date=January 2018}}{{context|date=January 2018}}\n{{Underlinked|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n\nOriginally published in 1959 as the American Hospital Formulary Service (AHFS) by the [[American Society of Health-System Pharmacists]], the '''AHFS DI''' is one of several compendiums<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=3b064b5a-3d91-4f4e-8161-1330fb6884fa|title=And then there were five: CMS approves Wolters Kluwer Lexi-Drugs\u00ae as the fifth recognized authoritative compendium {{!}} Lexology|last=ElizabethHalpern|first=Hogan Lovells-|last2=Langbein|first2=Stuart M.|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30|last3=Manning|first3=Meredith|last4=Roberts|first4=Beth L.|last5=Lakhani|first5=Ali}}</ref> approved by the [[Social Security Act]] ([https://www.ssa.gov/OP_Home/ssact/title18/1861.htm Section 1861(t)(2)(B)(ii)(I)]) as a source of off-label anti-[[cancer]] drug use.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Coverage Document|url=https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/details/medicare-coverage-document-details.aspx?MCDId=31&mcdtypena